<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06052g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06052g">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06052g"> 52(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bath (sink, float,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Si vous mettez l&apos;enfant <mark>au bain</mark> et que vous laissiez des joujoux &agrave; sa disposition, vous vous persuadez facilement que sa mani&egrave;re de se divertir n&apos;est plus celle que vous avez observ&eacute;e quelques minutes auparavant: l&apos;enfant essaie <mark>de faire plonger les objets flottants</mark> et, par contre, de faire nager les objets lourds; il &eacute;tudie en un mot les propri&eacute;t&eacute;s hydrostatiques de ses joujoux, et c&apos;est cette id&eacute;e seule qui l&apos;int&eacute;resse dans ce moment. <font color="green">[If you put the child in the bath and you leave toys at your disposal, you easily persuade yourself that his way of entertaining is no longer the one you observed a few minutes ago: the child tries to sink the objects that float and, on the other hand, to float heavy objects; he studies in a word the hydrostatic properties of his toys, and it is this idea alone which interests him at this moment.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 105</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
